comments.body:
@SteveL-MSFT Thanks!
I still haven't full understanding. Windows PowerShell Compatibility Pack is mostly for _backward compatibility_ with Windows PowerShell. It only makes sense for those features that will _never_ be ported. The rest needs to be implemented _here_, so far we can do it in part using WCP.

Apart from that we have and will have a lot of places in the code under `if Unix`. We have a lot of issues about the lack of dlls. We already have request to support framework-based distribution (not self-contained #6058). We have problems with Unix packaging. Using WCP and the _methods_ from the aforementioned blog brings us closer to addressing these issues significantly.
